What are shared libraries in Jenkins and why are they used in large-scale CI/CD setups?

Jenkins Shared Libraries are reusable Groovy code stored in a Git repo that multiple pipelines can import and use. In large scale setups 
like managing 400+ microservices, they eliminate code duplication, enforce consistency, and allow a single fix to propagate across 
all pipelines instantly.

Without Shared Library:
  Pipeline A → copy paste same code
  Pipeline B → copy paste same code
  Pipeline C → copy paste same code
  → 400 pipelines = 400 duplicate codes ❌
  → Change one thing = update 400 files ❌

With Shared Library:
  Common code → ONE place (Git repo)
  Pipeline A → calls shared library
  Pipeline B → calls shared library
  Pipeline C → calls shared library
  → Change one thing = all 400 updated ✅
--------------

Simple Analogy

Shared Library = Python pip package / Java Maven dependency

Just like:
  import boto3          ← reusable library
  import requests       ← reusable library

In Jenkins:
  @Library('my-shared-lib')   ← reusable pipeline code

---------------
Folder Structure of Shared Library

jenkins-shared-library/        ← Git repo
      │
      ├── vars/                ← Global functions (most used)
      │     ├── dockerBuild.groovy
      │     ├── deployToEKS.groovy
      │     ├── sendSlackAlert.groovy
      │     └── runTerraform.groovy
      │
      ├── src/                 ← Classes (advanced)
      │     └── com/company/
      │           ├── Docker.groovy
      │           └── Kubernetes.groovy
      │
      └── resources/           ← Static files
            └── scripts/
                  └── health-check.sh

